I'd like to see a machine added (and reviewed by the top-level maintainers) before we add the whole jabil team to OWNERS.  I want to make sure you're going in the right direction and following our overall meta-layer guidelines before turning you loose to merge anything you want.
The dts file used in our machine is currently under Torvalds review, we will add the machine here once it is approved.
We recently removed meta-security everywhere, because it isn't needed.
Elsewhere you indicated this was an x86 server.
Please fix the mixture of tabs and spaces (use spaces everywhere).
I don't see meta-jabil/meta-common in your bblayers.conf.sample.  Is this intentional?
BBFILES of layer.conf in meta-jabil points to meta-common, so I didn't add meta-common in bblayers.conf.sample
Ok.  I see that.  But then why are you bothering with a meta-common/conf/layer.conf?  It seems duplicative.
I think wrapping common recipes into meta-common. This way meta-jabil can be more concise and see supported layers.

Having meta-jabil/meta-common seems fine as a layer.  Having meta-jabil as a layer seems fine.  What doesn't seem fine is having two layers that are effectively the same thing.

Right now meta-jabil is effectively the same thing as meta-common, but you've got this duplicated conf/local.conf for them both.  I would suggest dropping one of them.
ok, thanks for your suggestion. I gave up on meta-common.

meta-perl and meta-webserver should be removed now.

Apologies for the churn here.  You adding a new meta-layer made me question why we have so many of these on many systems and I've removed them from the tree elsewhere.

Hi sir,
Is there anything wrong with this commit, please?



BR

We need to get a jabil group set up for holding the people covered by their CLA in order to get Jenkins to automatically trigger.  I will manually approve Jenkins now since David is covered by their CLA.

David: See this email for some of the process in order to get Jenkins running on your commits automatically.  One issue I see with your company's CLA is that nobody is listed as the CLA Manager, so we can't add anyone to the "jabil-authorized-owners" group in order for your company to self-manage their contributors.
Thanks for your advice. We have updated the CLA. Please add our members to the "jabil-authorized-owners" group.

David,

Since your company has added everyone to the CLA managers (which is slightly unusual), I'd appreciate if you can update the groups as appropriately.  I've added you to jabil/authorized-owners.  Please add all your peer CLA managers from your company's schedule A.

https://gerrit.openbmc.org/admin/groups/a51516050c70e6785a7d51b80b139a510b4e1510,members

You can also add them to the group jabil/ci-authorized.

https://gerrit.openbmc.org/admin/groups/9c2ec2c2a3367aaf801caeb7e46c88c94a904512,members

You have a large number of people here who are not covered by your CLA.  You should probably get that fixed.

https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/1H5DBebQgFmGt6Lpzs7K4z2-aFQKRTyDW

Hi sir,
Could you please trigger Jenkins once?

BR

David

@David, Hi, I've been on vacation and just got back today.

I tried to trigger this one and got a Jenkins failure (https://jenkins.openbmc.org/job/CI-MISC/job/openbmc-userid-validation/lastFailedBuild/console).  It seems like the email address you've added to the commits still doesn't match the email address in Gerrit.  It may be a matter of simple capitalization.  You should see "Owner" and "Author" here are both listed as "David Wang" but with a different icon, which means Gerrit is not seeing them as the same person.  This causes our code that looks up the contributor to figure out which CLA group they are in to fail.
